          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><p><em>将精彩的阅读推荐发送到您的收件箱。 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/newsletters?sub=410&amp;mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">订阅</a>每周的图书时事通讯。</em></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 11 Aug 2023 20:39:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/15-books-we-read-this-week-6b909f75</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/15-books-we-read-this-week-6b909f75<category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Hunter Biden Plea Talks Break Down as DOJ Names Special Counsel]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>司法部长梅里克·加兰（Merrick Garland）授予美国检察官大卫·韦斯（David Weiss）更广泛的权力，以对总统的儿子提出指控<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001128628"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=8F100B27-8D38-40F9-9043-D86075174137&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fmerrick-garland-names-david-weiss-as-special-counsel-in-hunter-biden-investigation-a2ad0ba4&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">司法部长梅里克·加兰周五表示，他将把大卫·韦斯的身份改为亨特·拜登调查中的特别检察官。照片：斯蒂芬妮·斯卡布勒/美联社<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001128628"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/sadie-gurman" itemprop="url" rel="author">Sadie Gurman</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/aruna-viswanatha" itemprop="url" rel="author">Aruna Viswanatha</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 8 月 11 日下午 4:39（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/merrick-garland-names-david-weiss-as-special-counsel-in-hunter-biden-investigation-a2ad0ba4"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>华盛顿——周五，司法部长梅里克·加兰（Merrick Garland）任命特拉华州联邦检察官戴维·韦斯（David Weiss）为特别检察官，在认罪谈判破裂后继续起诉亨特·拜登，这为<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/hunter-biden-plea-deal-limbo-republicans-749b5187?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">这场长期上演的法律剧</a>揭开了充满政治色彩的新篇章。拜登， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/joe-and-hunter-biden-ignores-political-perils-and-embraces-scandal-plagued-son-f105aee2?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">竞选连任</a>。</p><p>这项任命允许韦斯在他认为合适的任何地区而不仅仅是在特拉华州起诉亨特·拜登，就在韦斯在法庭文件中表示与拜登的认罪谈判陷入僵局的同一天，检察官预计针对他的案件将会结束受审。</p><p>韦斯要求特拉华州的一名联邦法官驳回之前针对亨特·拜登提起的税务案件，称检察官需要在其他地方审理此案，包括在加利福尼亚州，拜登在本案有争议的几年里居住在那里。</p><p>加兰说，韦斯周二告诉他，他的调查“已经达到了他应该继续担任特别检察官的工作的阶段，他要求被任命为特别检察官”。加兰此前坚称韦斯拥有所有必要的资源和自主权，他表示此举“重申了韦斯先生拥有进行彻底调查所需的权力，并仅根据事实继续独立采取他认为适当的步骤”和法律。”</p><p>亨特·拜登的律师克里斯·克拉克表示，拜登的法律团队仍然相信他们可以不经审判就解决此案。他说：“我们相信，当所有这些操作结束后，我的客户将会下定决心，并成功地继续他的生活。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834291?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">司法部长梅里克·加兰周五指出与亨特·拜登调查有关的“特殊情况”。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：德鲁·安格勒/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>韦斯的任命使司法部陷入前所未有的境地，三名不同的特别检察官正在调查总统、他的儿子，以及总统可能在 2024 年竞选中的主要竞争对手、共和党领跑者<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/donald-trump">唐纳德·特朗普</a>。</p><p>特别检察官杰克·史密斯<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-trial-special-counsel-jack-smith-prosecutors-team-20d57b78?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">指控特朗普</a>不当扣留机密文件，并单独密谋非法推翻他 2020 年大选的失败；特朗普在这两起案件中均表示无罪。另一位特别检察官罗伯特·胡尔（Robert Hur）在拜登总统的家中和办公室发现了他入主白宫之前的此类文件后，一直在调查拜登总统<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/robert-hur-brings-experience-with-political-pressure-to-special-counsel-role-11673562204?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">对机密材料的处理情况</a>。</p><p>韦斯已经基本上独立运作，上个月告诉立法者，他“从未被剥夺在任何司法管辖区提起指控的权力”。</p><p>新的身份意味着韦斯不受司法部领导层的日常监督，尽管他必须向高级官员通报他寻求做出的重大决定。他还必须撰写并提交一份工作报告，然后司法部长可以将其公开。如果司法部长拒绝他的任何行动，加兰必须根据特别顾问的规定向国会解释。</p><div class="media-object scope-web,mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>国会共和党人一直在调查涉及亨特·拜登和拜登家族的商业交易，并谴责现在岌岌可危的认罪安排与司法部对特朗普的强硬立场相比过于宽松。两名调查人员指控不当政治干预，在一定程度上加剧了批评。</p><p> “让我们弄清楚今天的举动到底是什么，”一直<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/gop-lawmakers-two-jobs-investigating-bidens-managing-firebrands-a43c414?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">领导国会调查的</a>众议院监督委员会主席詹姆斯·科默（肯塔基州共和党人）说。 “拜登司法部正试图阻碍国会监督。”</p><p>众议院司法委员会主席、众议员吉姆·乔丹（俄亥俄州共和党人）对加兰的行为表示怀疑，尽管他曾在此案中呼吁特别检察官。 “首先，大卫·韦斯说他没有所需的权力，想要特别检察官的地位。然后，他说他拥有他需要的所有权力，”乔丹周五发推文。 “现在，他获得了特别检察官的地位，因为他并没有真正拥有他需要的权力？有什么不对劲。”</p><p>参议院司法委员会主席、伊利诺伊州民主党参议员迪克·杜宾 (Dick Durbin) 表示，司法部长的举动表明他希望避免“司法部出现政治化”，并补充说这一立场“与司法部的政治化形成鲜明对比”。前总统特朗普一再努力利用司法部和总检察长作为他的私人律师。”</p><p>一位知情人士称，在宣布这一计划之前，白宫和亨特·拜登的律师均未获悉该计划。白宫没有发表评论，而是将问题转交给司法部和亨特·拜登的法律团队。</p><p>这项任命是对亨特·拜登的财务、商业交易以及有据可查的毒瘾和酗酒成瘾的曲折且具有政治爆炸性的调查的最新转折。</p><p>自 2018 年韦斯领导下以来，调查一直在进行。韦斯被特朗普任命为美国检察官，并在拜登政府期间继续留任，负责监督刑事调查。加兰表示<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/garland-defends-independence-of-hunter-biden-plea-deal-amid-gop-criticism-e8d8d0dd?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">，他让韦斯可以自由地</a>进行他认为合适的调查。</p><p>亨特·拜登上个月对联邦税务指控<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/hunter-biden-plea-deal-in-jeopardy-ff556d70?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">表示无罪</a>，这是一个令人惊讶的逆转，此前美国地区法官玛丽莲·诺雷卡拒绝签署他早些时候达成的对税务指控认罪并签署一项单独协议来解决枪支指控的协议。 。法官表示，她需要更多信息和时间来审查该交易，并援引了她所说的非典型条款。周五，检察官表示，挽救枪支协议的谈判也破裂了。法官要求亨特·拜登的团队在周一之前对政府的文件做出回应。</p><p>在认罪听证会上，检察官还透露，他们仍在调查拜登，并表示他可能面临额外指控，包括可能违反要求外国政府或公司的游说者注册该作品的法律。</p><p>参与调查的两名国税局刑事特工声称，政治考虑似乎影响了调查各个阶段的调查决定，而且拜登似乎获得了其他调查目标所没有的优惠待遇。</p><p>特工们告诉立法者，检察官和韦斯早些时候建议对拜登提出重罪税收指控，尽管拜登最终得到的协议仅涉及两项故意不缴纳联邦所得税的轻罪指控，而且韦斯的办公室也同意建议仅缓刑一次。税务重罪可能会导致入狱，但最终的判决取决于负责此案的法官。</p><p>在上个月的一篇专栏文章中，美国国税局特工约瑟夫·齐格勒 (Joseph Ziegler) <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-special-counsel-for-hunter-biden-justice-irs-tax-whistleblower-2fe10db1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">敦促加兰任命一名特别检察官</a>来独立审查此事。 “我在调查过程中看到的情况完全不符合常态，”齐格勒说。</p><p>韦斯在六月的一封信中告诉众议院司法委员会：“我确实被授予对此事的最终权力，包括决定何时、何地以及是否提出指控的责任，以及做出必要决定以维护起诉公正性的责任。”</p><p>在随后的一封信中，韦斯表示，他从未寻求任命为特别检察官，一位知情人士证实，周二是他第一次要求担任特别检察官。</p><p>根据拜登与检察官达成的协议，他承认2017年和2018年的年收入都超过150万美元，其中大部分来自国外。拜登还承认，他与一名会计师合作准备了纳税申报表，但当时从未真正提交过纳税申报表，也没有支付他所欠的税款，当时他对强效可卡因上瘾。</p><p> 2021 年，拜登的一名同事向国税局支付了 190 万美元，用于支付这些税款、利息和罚款。</p><p class="articleTagLine"> ——安妮·林斯基对本文做出了贡献。</p><p>写信给 Sadie Gurman <a href="mailto:sadie.gurman@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">(sadie.gurman@wsj.com)</a>和 Aruna Viswanatha ( <a href="mailto:aruna.viswanatha@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">aruna.viswanatha@wsj.com</a> )</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 11 Aug 2023 20:39:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/merrick-garland-names-david-weiss-as-special-counsel-in-hunter-biden-investigation-a2ad0ba4</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/merrick-garland-names-david-weiss-as-special-counsel-in-hunter-biden-investigation-a2ad0ba4<author><![CDATA[Sadie GurmanAruna Viswanatha]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>大卫·韦斯</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘The Bee Sting’ Review: When Did It All Go Wrong?]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>在保罗·默里的小说中，一个富裕的家庭的地毯被拔掉了。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11380450262913973852004590140174222239584"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833512?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCredit">照片：盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11380450262913973852004590140174222239584"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/sam-sacks" itemprop="url" rel="author">萨姆·萨克斯</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 8 月 11 日下午 4:03（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-bee-sting-paul-murray-fiction-review-when-did-it-all-go-wrong-79df015d"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>保罗·默里在他的长篇小说《蜂蜇》中讲述了爱尔兰本土红松鼠的悲伤故事。一个多世纪前，白金汉公爵向爱尔兰乡村庄园的一对新婚夫妇送了一个柳条篮，里面装有十几只北美灰松鼠。当礼篮在草坪上被隆重地打开时，松鼠们就冲进了森林。很快，“就像殖民主义的寓言一样”，它们在整个岛上繁殖起来。灰松鼠携带松鼠痘病毒，但对其免疫，这种病毒会使红松鼠的嘴周围出现病变，使它们无法进食。就这样，因为一份结婚礼物，整个物种被推向灭绝的边缘。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/3e98949a-0a13-451e-86b6-aed43c023259.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>巴尼斯家族是默里先生家族传奇中遭受灾难困扰的爱尔兰本土家族。从外表上看，他们是这座无名小城市羡慕的对象。迪基是一家家长，经营着从父亲那里继承的当地汽车经销店，并一直住在他儿时的房子里，后院有一片巨大的林地。他的妻子伊梅尔达是一位著名的美女，她像武术黑带一样挥舞着信用卡。他们的孩子 Cass 和 PJ 在物质条件优越的情况下长大。这是一次完美的国内伊卡洛斯飞行，让坠机坠落到地球上。</p><p>造成这一切的原因是2008年银行业危机后的爱尔兰经济萧条，导致迪基的经销店濒临破产，并迫使伊梅尔达在 eBay 上出售她的名牌服装，这是一种耻辱。财务崩溃对家庭成员来说是一种违约行为——正如 PJ 所说，“缓慢而有条不紊地破坏了他认为真实的一切”——并使他们对以前认为理所当然的行为产生了深深的怀疑。伊梅尔达抱怨某种长期存在的人格缺陷，导致迪基被动地接受自己的毁灭。卡斯承诺进入三一学院的入学资格现在面临风险，她开始想知道她的父母还隐瞒了什么。为什么披风上的家庭照片中没有结婚照？酒吧里那个醉酒的老家伙说伊梅尔达曾经和迪基死去的弟弟弗兰克订婚，这是什么意思？</p><p>随着《蜜蜂蜇伤》继续巴尼斯夫妇的故事，它开始解开过去的事件，通过模糊的因果关系向后移动，就像倒转的多米诺骨牌视频一样。 “当你回顾过去时，你无法判断自己究竟错在哪里，”迪基认为。 “这是一次失误吗？”本书所探讨的问题是为什么事情会这样发生。每个家庭的背景中是否都存在某种原罪，预示着堕落的到来，松鼠被释放、未来被决定的决定性时刻？另一本书可能会通过调查命运或机会来探索这个谜团，但《蜂蜇》是一部爱尔兰小说，充满了迷信和预言（伊梅尔达的阿姨罗丝会读茶叶，并且有“闪现”的千里眼），所以这个问题更好措辞：有诅咒之类的东西吗？ </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
        "><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/15-books-we-read-this-week-6b909f75" target="_blank" class="icon none">本周我们读的 15 本书</a></h4><div class="media-object-interactiveLink"><div class="image-container"><a class="interactive-link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/15-books-we-read-this-week-6b909f75"><img width="16" height="10" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832456?width=639&amp;height=393" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><span class="image-interactive-icon">
                </span></a></div><div class="wsj-article-caption"><span class="wsj-article-credit"></span></div></div><p>乔治·奥威尔的婚姻、早期好莱坞明星不可思议的生活、改变美国民间音乐的人等等。</p></div></div><p>如果说这部小说是爱尔兰小说，那就是另一种更讨人喜欢的概括：从风格上讲，它很出色，其特点是柔和、引人入胜的散文和超自然的讲故事感。即使牢记 20 世纪爱尔兰文学的奇迹，这个小岛上仍然涌现的写作质量仍然令人惊叹。包括默里先生在内的四位爱尔兰作家刚刚入围布克奖长名单，该奖向世界各地的英语小说开放。该国的人才点名包括：安妮·恩莱特 (Anne Enright)、凯文·巴里 (Kevin Barry)、萨拉·波美 (Sara Baume)、唐纳尔·瑞安 (Donal Ryan)、埃米尔·麦克布莱德 (Eimear McBride)、约翰·班维尔 (John Banville)、克莱尔·路易斯·贝内特 (Claire-Louis Bennett)、塞巴斯蒂安·巴里 (Sebastian Barry)、克莱尔·基冈 (Claire Keegan)、科尔姆·托宾 (Colm Tóibín)、艾玛·多诺霍 (Emma Donoghue) 和伯纳德·麦克拉弗蒂 (Bernard MacLaverty)，提供了一份不完整的名单——也非常多样化，包括对光荣文学传统的更新以及蓬勃发展的前卫艺术。</p><p>穆雷在这一切中的地位似乎正在发生变化。在《蜂蜇》之前，称他为爱尔兰最好的喜剧小说家是有道理的，因为他的搞笑而恐怖的寄宿学校欢闹剧《Skippy Dies》（2010）以及较小程度上的《标记与虚空》（2015） ），一部尖锐的银行讽刺作品被叙事噱头削弱了一些。但这部新小说虽然常常很有趣，但有着更严肃的意图。默里先生总是能够令人眼花缭乱、令人愉悦，但他以前从未塑造过具有如此深度或悲剧能力的角色。</p><p> 《蜜蜂蜇伤》的细节如此丰富，读起来就像四本书交织在一起一样，因为巴恩斯家族的每个成员都被分配了一个以自由间接引语呈现的冗长部分。卡斯在高中的最后一年，主要专注于保持她受欢迎且控制欲强的好朋友伊莱恩的好感，而默里先生很好地将幻灭、同侪压力和性觉醒等元素融合在一起，这些元素标志着她陷入困境成熟。 PJ 更年轻，也更理智，大部分时间都由他自己决定，他的部分采取了惊悚片的形式：受到恶霸的威胁，他考虑逃到都柏林去和他在网上认识的一个朋友住在一起，而这个朋友，很明显对读者来说，是一个伪装成孩子的掠夺性成年人。</p><p>当小说占据伊梅尔达的脑海时，它完全陷入了过去。默里先生借用了《尤利西斯》中莫莉·布鲁姆的独白来想象这个朴实的人物，他的思想没有标点符号地表达（尽管大写字母仍然表示新句子的开始，因此章节并不难读）。伊梅尔达有着“可以剥掉油漆的口音”，出身于贫困和暴力，是一位残暴的前拳击手的独生女，而她与盖尔足球明星、富裕的巴恩斯家族的金童弗兰克的求爱，是她一生的追求。逃生手段。当弗兰克在一场车祸中去世时——他穿着结婚礼服被埋葬——伊梅尔达又陷入了不确定的境地，直到她抓住了同样茫然和悲伤的迪基提供的救生衣。</p><p>迪基是否表现得很有男子气概，在婚姻和家族事业中接替了他哥哥的位置，或者他的替代是否违反了自然秩序？这些章节从他的角度回顾了他的大学时光，虽然不应该在这里剧透，但它们介绍了更多他看似令人垂涎的家庭生活本应隐藏的秘密。当这些秘密面临曝光的威胁时，一种复杂且高度有益的模糊感开始附着在情节的转折上。一种可怕的不可避免的感觉继续向巴恩斯家族袭来，预示着他们的解散，但也很明显，他们在选择和坚持自己的道路上是同谋，而诚实的变革性行为可能会改变他们的结果。</p><p>通过一系列悬疑的曲折和佯攻，默里先生分别推进了角色的故事，然后集体推进，最后一个精彩的部分将四个人聚集在一起。只有在<em>戏剧的</em>最后<em>一击中</em>，当巧合带来真正的四向碰撞时，戏剧才会给人一种粗暴、被操纵的感觉，而不是有机地展开。</p><p>但到目前为止，我们已经花了很多时间与角色相处，我们对他们生活的投资已经得到了保证。这本有点十九世纪风格的小说的优点在于，它允许在因果链之外推动每个人前进的现实时刻。令人震惊的同情之光撕裂了秘密和自我参与的帷幕。考虑到父亲身份的脆弱性，迪基认为：“你无法保护你所爱的人——这是历史的教训，因此他突然意识到，爱一个人就意味着要承受极大的痛苦。”后来，在一次罕见的对弟弟的关心中，卡斯也有了同样的认识：“这一定就是为人父母的感觉，不断担心你的孩子在你移开视线的那一刻就会被消灭。这一定就是他们如此疯狂的原因。”在坦率与欺骗、无助与绝望的预防的摇摇欲坠的混合中，默里先生描绘了一幅高度但真实的家庭之爱的肖像。</p><p>奇怪的是没有结婚照怎么办？卡斯听到的解释是，当伊梅尔达开车去教堂时，一只蜜蜂被困在她的面纱后面并蜇了她的眼睛下方，留下了一道伤痕，但她的虚荣心不允许记录下来。卡斯带着十几岁的气愤，把这个故事视为她父母有多么可笑的证据，也是他们失败的预兆。真正的原因在《蜂蜇》的过程中逐渐揭示出来，事实证明，它更复杂、更人性化，也更可怕。他们应该选择哪一个：继续在令人安慰的谎言的迷宫中前进，还是接受痛苦的后果——也许还有自由——说出事情的真相？</p><p class="articleTagLine"> -先生。萨克斯是《华尔街日报》的小说评论家。</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 11 Aug 2023 20:03:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-bee-sting-paul-murray-fiction-review-when-did-it-all-go-wrong-79df015d</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-bee-sting-paul-murray-fiction-review-when-did-it-all-go-wrong-79df015d<author><![CDATA[Sam Sacks]]></author><category>图书</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>图书</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘The Romantic’ Review: Scenes of a Century]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>威廉·博伊德的全景小说讲述了拿破仑的最后一战、斯里兰卡的恐怖以及与拜伦勋爵的谈话。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11667163785710763363504590140232817348898"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833545?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">日内瓦迪奥达蒂别墅 (Villa Diodati)，由 William Purser 雕刻。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：G. Dagli Orti/Bridgeman Images </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11667163785710763363504590140232817348898"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"><span class="author" itemprop="name">布鲁克·艾伦</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 11 日下午 3:54 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-romantic-william-boyd-fiction-review-scenes-of-a-century-fc855e30"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>从他的第一部小说《非洲好人》开始，威廉·博伊德在四十多年的时间里赢得了声誉，成为可靠、有文化、令人愉快的商业小说的提供者，这些小说通常以有吸引力的历史或地理环境为背景。他的最新作品《浪漫主义》，就像它的几部前作，包括广受欢迎的《任何人心》一样，被博伊德先生称为“一生小说”：对主人公从摇篮到坟墓的描述。必然是他所经历的时代的写照。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/dc3c8cb1-8a29-4235-8fb6-02804ed85976.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> 《任何人的心》、《甜蜜的爱抚》和《新的忏悔》都带着主角穿越了 20 世纪，也就是作者的祖国。不过，在《浪漫派》中，博伊德先生回到了 19 世纪。卡舍尔·格雷维尔·罗斯 (Cashel Greville Ross) 出生于 1700 年代末，是一位爱尔兰地主的私生子。在漫长的一生中，他目睹了本世纪一些最戏剧性的场景。他目睹了滑铁卢的行动，目睹了斯里兰卡第三次康提战争期间的大屠杀，与拜伦和雪莱一家一起游历意大利（他甚至帮助拜伦在维亚雷焦的海滩上火化了雪莱的尸体），遇见了——也失去了——他的爱人。拉文纳的生活（拉斐拉·雷佐伯爵夫人饰），在伦敦格鲁布街当作家，在马萨诸塞州康科德附近耕种土地。（博伊德先生令人惊讶地抵制住了让他的英雄与邻近的超验主义者擦肩而过的诱惑），去了非洲在寻找尼罗河的源头时，他遇到了理查德·伯顿，并与约翰·汉宁·斯皮克发生冲突，成为尼加拉瓜驻的里雅斯特领事（别问！），并在威尼斯结束了他的一生，并被埋葬在圣米歇尔岛。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
        "><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/15-books-we-read-this-week-6b909f75" target="_blank" class="icon none">本周我们读的 15 本书</a></h4><div class="media-object-interactiveLink"><div class="image-container"><a class="interactive-link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/15-books-we-read-this-week-6b909f75"><img width="16" height="10" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832456?width=639&amp;height=393" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><span class="image-interactive-icon">
                </span></a></div><div class="wsj-article-caption"><span class="wsj-article-credit"></span></div></div><p>乔治·奥威尔的婚姻、早期好莱坞明星不可思议的生活、改变美国民间音乐的人等等。</p></div></div><p>这一切应该很有趣。但可惜的是，《浪漫派》是一部疲惫不堪、毫无生气的作品，写起来就好像博伊德先生正在尽职尽责地使用他创造的公式，并且之前使用过它以获得更好的效果。部分问题在于罗斯缺乏个性。在《卫报》一篇关于这部一生小说的文章中，博伊德先生声称读者“开始认同中心人物……”。 。 。以一种不同的、更投入的方式，因为他们拥有所有必要的信息，无论是重要的还是无关紧要的。”好吧，我们可能已经获得了有关罗斯生活的大量信息，但事实是他太平淡了，无法认同，而且肯定太平淡了，不足以作为一部长小说的主线。 “他是谁？”罗斯曾一度沉思自己。 “他是什么？构成他现在的‘是’的‘是’是什么？”答案并不是我们太在意，而是罗斯只是一个文学噱头，用来将各种经过仔细研究的历史场景联系在一起。</p><p>像《烟草因素》（约翰·巴特）和《梅森与狄克逊》（托马斯·品钦）这样的小说可能会令人恼火，因为它们的作者痛苦而自觉地努力将历史语言和思潮融入他们的个人风格。博伊德先生甚至没有尝试一下。罗斯和他的许多朋友和同事基本上都说现代英语，偶尔会加入“withal”等句号。“尊敬的先生，”罗斯有一次对他的上级说。 “你从什么时候开始成为康提风俗专家了？”在对话中，像“钱换果酱”（第一次世界大战期间创造的）这样完全不合时宜的表达方式会时不时地出现——这不是作者的笑话，而是显然因为博伊德先生懒得想出这个词。 19世纪的人实际上可能会说的话。那么罗斯所说的这句话呢？ “真可惜。拜伦在比萨。谁能想到呢？真的吗？有时，叙事会从 20 世纪的用语（已经够糟糕了）发展到 21 世纪的用语，比如雪莱圈子被称为“这些特权人士”。正如罗斯所说，天哪！</p><p>博伊德先生选择了 19 世纪最著名的三位演说家——拜伦、雪莱和伯顿——作为他的角色，然后几乎没有给他们任何对话，这一事实表明这本小说是多么三心二意。人们可以理解，对于一个现代作家来说，为传奇天才发明对话一定是令人生畏的，但尝试至少不会有一点乐趣吗？相反，博伊德先生采取了简单的方法，简单地描述了这些著名人物的说话方式。 “伯顿说啊说啊，让每个人都筋疲力尽。 。 。卡舍尔溜走了。他想象伯顿对盐窖和空瓶波特酒喋喋不休，非常高兴有他们作为听众。他显然是一个聪明人，非常聪明——但是却被限制在一个房间里和他在一起。 。 ”。从对伯顿性格的了解来看，人们可以相信这一点。但有精神的小说家不会在挑战面前退缩。</p><p>由于在这个流浪汉故事的每一站，作者总是顽强地把目光投向他的英雄的下一个目的地，有前途的人物和情况突然出现，只是被毫不客气地扔在几页上。罗斯与他的父亲盖伊·斯蒂尔威尔爵士的复杂关系一开始很有趣，但当盖伊爵士去世时，他在儿子的生活中似乎并不比过往游行中的其他人更有意义。罗斯在写作生涯中遇到的几位伦敦文学家——<em>沙龙作家</em>埃塔琳达·达文波特和不诚实的出版商普维斯·耶尔弗顿——都很优秀，但他们很快就被抛在了后面。罗斯与拜伦的情人克莱尔·克莱尔蒙特享受的田园诗般的生活提供了令人兴奋的可能性，但它以失败告终，罗斯继续前进。博伊德先生偶尔会谈到参与 19 世纪生活的真实感受，就像罗斯在阔别多年后回到英国时，对铁路旅行的革命性影响感到震惊一样：“一切都变得‘正常’了。” ’以惊人的速度。”但这些都是转瞬即逝的时刻。</p><p>人们想知道博伊德先生的目标读者是谁？任何对拜伦和雪莱圈子、非洲探索或伦敦文学真正感兴趣的人，都不会在这些页面中发现任何重要内容。任何想要寻找引人入胜的爱情故事的人都不会在罗斯和他的拉斐拉的传统浪漫故事中找到这样的故事。这本小说可以作为新手对这一时期的介绍，有点像 19 世纪的 101。但对于博伊德先生享有盛誉的作家来说，设定的门槛很低。</p><p class="articleTagLine"> -多发性硬化症。艾伦经常为《华尔街日报》撰写书籍和艺术文章。她在本宁顿学院的监狱教育计划中任教。</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 11 Aug 2023 19:54:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-romantic-william-boyd-fiction-review-scenes-of-a- century-fc855e30</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-romantic-william-boyd-fiction-review-scenes-of-a- century-fc855e30<category>图书</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>威廉·博伊德</category><category>图书</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘Finding W.H. Hudson’ Review: The Enigmatic Birdman]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>这位致力于保护英格兰鸟类的人的神秘而矛盾的生活。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11667163785710763363504590140661223878380"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833372?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">弗兰克·布鲁克斯 (Frank Brooks) 创作的 WH 哈德森 (WH Hudson) 肖像细节，悬挂在英国桑迪皇家鸟类保护学会总部的壁炉上方。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：康纳·马克·詹姆森</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11667163785710763363504590140661223878380"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"><span class="author" itemprop="name">克里斯托夫·伊姆舍尔</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 11 日下午 3:45 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/finding-w-h-hudson-review-the-enigmatic-birdman-bcff07e1"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>威廉·亨利·哈德森（William Henry Hudson，1841-1922 年）是英国皇家鸟类保护学会的创始成员之一，当他高高地骑在 Sunbeam 自行车上，在英国乡村漫步，寻找他心爱的羽毛鸟时，一定引起了人们的注意。朋友们。他身材瘦小，穿着粗花呢、背心和系带靴子，看上去比英国人还要英国人，帽子里藏着一块湿手帕，让自己保持凉爽。有些人认为，哈德逊目光敏锐，不断移动，就像一只野鸟——也许是一只鹰，或者一只鹰。康纳·马克·詹姆森在他的新传记中报道说，他的笑声听起来像绿色啄木鸟的声音，并补充说，他再也听不到那只鸟的声音而不想起哈德逊。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/5c97296d-3812-49f1-a3ab-57624157eade.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>在詹姆森先生在英国皇家鸟类保护协会办公室工作的 25 年里，一幅哈德逊的肖像画，手持双筒望远镜，眯着眼睛，在壁炉架上默默地凝视着他。詹姆森先生是剑桥郡的作家和自然资源保护主义者，他决心恢复哈德森的声音。他梳理了档案，寻找他的英雄的踪迹，并蜿蜒穿越英国——有时自己骑着自行车——重现哈德森的旅行（当他在哈德森也听到过的地方发现一只金翅雀时，他感到非常高兴）。结果是一本活泼、对话式的书，散布着自传旁白，创造性地融合了侦探工作和叙事直觉（“我们只能猜测”），就像它的主题一样难以确定。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
        "><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/15-books-we-read-this-week-6b909f75" target="_blank" class="icon none">本周我们读的 15 本书</a></h4><div class="media-object-interactiveLink"><div class="image-container"><a class="interactive-link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/15-books-we-read-this-week-6b909f75"><img width="16" height="10" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832456?width=639&amp;height=393" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><span class="image-interactive-icon">
                </span></a></div><div class="wsj-article-caption"><span class="wsj-article-credit"></span></div></div><p>乔治·奥威尔的婚姻、早期好莱坞明星不可思议的生活、改变美国民间音乐的人等等。</p></div></div><p>如果最后的“寻找 WH Hudson”并没有真正“找到”WH Hudson，那也是理所当然的。哈德森甚至对他最亲密的朋友来说也是一个谜。首先，他并不是真正的英国人。吉列尔莫·恩里克（Guillermo Enrique）出生于阿根廷，父母来自美国，邻居们都称呼他为吉列尔莫·恩里克（Guillermo Enrique），他在潘帕斯草原上长大，周围有马、羊和牛群，一座小图书馆是他与高雅文化世界的唯一联系。哈德森后来烧毁了他的大部分信件，但这并没有阻止传记作者思考他 1874 年移民到英国的原因。在他的《生活在风声中》（2015 年）中，詹姆森先生的努力背后的模型文学评论家贾森·威尔逊提出了一个显而易见的问题：为什么像哈德森这样自称的自然爱好者会决定离开阿根廷这个拥有“广阔的空地、蓝色的天空和没有污染”的国家，并定居在烟灰覆盖、过度拥挤的地方伦敦？詹姆森先生补充了一个同样难以回答的让他全神贯注的问题：为什么一位南美博物学家几乎从到达的那一刻起，就如此热情地致力于拯救一个不属于他自己的国家的野生鸟类？</p><p>哈德逊的一生充满了矛盾。来到英国后，他投身于自然历史写作，源源不断地对南美和家养鸟类进行最美丽的描述，描绘出“云雀的满溢喜悦；黑帽的野性精神；柳鹪鹩的轻盈、细腻的温柔”（《英国鸟类》，1895）。尽管哈德森仍然坚称自己不是“你们这些该死的作家”，但他却因小说《绿楼》（1904）而闻名于世，小说中一名躲在树林里的委内瑞拉政治难民疯狂地爱上了一个女人。名为 Rima 的像鸟一样的丛林生物（事情的结局并不好）。哈德森的丰富遐想后来被拍成了一部好莱坞电影，由瘦长、整洁的安东尼·帕金斯和精灵般的奥黛丽·赫本搭档，奥黛丽·赫本看起来就像刚从更衣室里出来一样。可以说，这种虚假行为甚至更早开始：哈德森本人从未踏足过委内瑞拉的荒野。</p><p>哈德森并没有让人们轻易喜欢他。甚至在来英国之前，他就大声批评达尔文假设某种南美啄木鸟以地面为食，从未拜访过树木。达尔文调整了有问题的段落，但也对这位无礼的“同事”嗤之以鼻，他可能是一个不相信进化论的人，他如此无端地攻击了他。詹姆逊先生对哈德森的“直率”方法给予高度评价，但没有提到达尔文最终被证明是正确的——参见哈德森后来在《拉普拉塔的鸟类》（1920）中毫无歉意地承认。</p><p>尽管如此，哈德逊还是成功地吸引了一大群信徒，而詹姆森先生有时似乎对他们比对哈德逊本人更感兴趣。他的书中巧妙地描绘了哈德逊在英国皇家鸟类保护协会的女性合作者或朋友“唐·罗伯托”、苏格兰裔西班牙裔政治家坎宁安·格雷厄姆（Cunninghame Graham）的肖像，他喜欢在海德以高乔式的方式炫耀他的马。公园。我们还了解到很多崇拜他的文人，包括约瑟夫·康拉德、约翰·高尔斯华绥和弗吉尼亚·伍尔夫。 （埃兹拉·庞德对哈德森评价很高，把他写进了他的《诗章》中，称“哈迪……比在场的任何人都高”）。哈德逊的超级粉丝是古怪的玛格丽特·布鲁克，她是东印度领土沙捞越州王公的分居妻子，她和哈德逊一样对热带和鸟类学充满热情：她会坐在蓝色扶手椅、绿色扶手椅上迎接来到她的阿斯科特豪宅的访客。鹦鹉附在她的手腕上。</p><p>到詹姆森先生这本无可挑剔的研究著作结束时，吉列尔莫·恩里克的秘密基本完好无损。例如，我们仍然不知道如何看待他与年长得多的女房东艾米莉·温格雷夫（Emily Wingrave）的无性婚姻，或者他与记者的风流韵事（如果确实如此）。琳达·加德纳（Linda Gardiner）是哈德逊死后出版的《稀有、消失和失落的英国鸟类》（1923 年）的编辑。 WH Hudson 本人似乎也有点失落。</p><p>我们确实知道哈德森对离开祖国的决定感到后悔。 “当我想到那片土地如此丰富的鸟类时，”他在《拉普拉塔的鸟类》中叹息道，“我可能在两条向我敞开的道路中选择了一条错误的道路。”但也许正是这种自我造成的个人损失的经历，以及给予然后放弃的机会，使他能够更加关注另一种更大的损失——英国森林、田野和田野中大量鸟类的消失。海岸。詹姆森先生恰当地将 1921 年《羽毛法案》的通过描述为哈德森一生的亮点之一，该法案禁止在人类衣服中使用羽毛。</p><p> 《寻找 WH 哈德森》让我们更接近其奇怪的主角，尽管从未像哈德森本人与他的许多鸽子更接近。哈德森回忆起他年轻时在阿根廷的一次经历，当时他跟踪一只小红鹭（现在的条纹鹭）进入灯心草床，哈德森承认，他一开始无法在任何地方找到这只鸟，结果令他惊讶的是，它发现了它。就在他旁边，完美地模仿了冲刺，脖子和身体冻结成无懈可击的笔直形象。当哈德森绕着它盘旋时，这只鸟也转动了，它的动作与哈德森的完全一致，尽管它仍然僵硬地保持在原地。难以捉摸的哈德森在大自然中找到了自己的对手：“我无法停止欣赏，并认为以前从未有过如此美丽的东西挡住了我的路。”</p><p class="articleTagLine"> -先生。伊姆舍尔是《自然历史诗学》一书的作者，该书有新版本，并附有罗莎蒙德·珀塞尔的照片。</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 11 Aug 2023 19:45:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/finding-wh-hudson-review-the-enigmatic-birdman-bcff07e1</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/finding-wh-hudson-review-the-enigmatic-birdman-bcff07e1<category>图书</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>自然环境</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>英国皇家鸟类保护协会</category><category>图书</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>自然环境</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Here’s What a $5 Million Retirement Looks Like in America]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>退休人员公开他们的财务生活以及他们如何度过时间和金钱<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832718/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="身着粉红色衣服的退休人员帕特·弗雷 (Pat Frey) 经常与朋友一起在大自然中散步。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>身着粉红色衣服的退休人员帕特·弗雷 (Pat Frey) 经常与朋友一起在大自然中散步。丽贝卡·斯坦普夫 (Rebecca Stumpf) 的《华尔街日报》<span>丽贝卡·斯坦普夫 (Rebecca Stumpf) 的《华尔街日报》</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001122102"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001122102"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/veronica-dagher" itemprop="url" rel="author">维罗妮卡·达格尔</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/anne-tergesen" itemprop="url" rel="author">安妮·特格森</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 11 日上午 5:30 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/heres-what-a-5-million-retirement-looks-like-in-america-1abc76d9"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>多少钱都无法让退休后无忧无虑，但 500 万美元可能就差不多了。</p><p>很少有美国人能够在 401(k) 计划和个人退休账户中存下接近这一金额的钱。根据<a href="https://www.ebri.org/" target="_blank" class="icon none">员工福利研究所</a>使用 2019 年消费者财务调查对退休账户进行的分析，500 万美元的退休储蓄金使您跻身前 0.1% 的家庭之列。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="1092" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/d663f044-8f28-4ec7-8377-2302a6c566d6-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>为了了解 500 万美元可以在退休后购买什么，我们采访了全国各地拥有该金额储蓄的退休人员。</p><p>大多数人从未想过会成为百万富翁，但从职业生涯的早期就勤于储蓄。</p><p>尽管与<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/retirement-under-1-million-america-846a6ab6?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">我们介绍的许多退休人员</a>相比，他们不太担心自己的钱花光了，但他们并不都过着奢侈的生活。有些人已经很多年没有买新衣服了。其他人继续兼职工作。</p><p>他们在环球旅行上挥霍无度，但像大多数年长的美国人一样，担心自己的健康和家人。</p><p>仅靠金钱也无法解决退休人员面临的另一个问题：如何在人生的这一章中找到目的和意义？ </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/archibald/1JhIu4HsU3kUrK8q6t8nArRD6-qm34M9iySjy14qk7vc-chapter-1.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>保罗·谢姆韦尔 (Paul Shemwell) 在驾驶商用飞机和喷气式战斗机四十年后于 12 月退休。</p><p>尽管这位 65 岁的老人感觉自己的财务状况很安全，已经攒下了约 610 万美元，但他还没有制定接下来的飞行计划。</p><p>对于这位前飞行员来说，这种随意的态度是一个巨大的改变，他在空军的 13 年中磨练了自己的战略思维能力。他的服役经历也教会他仔细权衡自己的选择，这一理念指导着他的退休生活。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/2decacce-5119-4fbc-9b6f-3b2bd857ad6d.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>在<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/LUV" class="">西南航空公司</a>工作 28 年后，他不再乘坐飞机<span class="company-name-type">，</span>但旅行仍然是他的热情所在。他计划今年秋天进行四次旅行，这种旅行癖让他每月花费约 3,000 美元。他每月还要花费大约 9,000 美元用于财产税、房屋和汽车保险等费用。</p><p>他的一天通常从锻炼或网球课开始。作为一名狂热的滑雪爱好者，他已经购买了本赛季的通行证，并计划每年至少进行一次水肺潜水旅行。</p><p>谢姆韦尔拒绝了几份重返驾驶舱的工作机会，部分原因是他不需要钱。</p><p>他计划在达到完全退休年龄后领取<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/social-security-payment-increase-cola-2024-retirement-a3fce38e?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">社会保障</a>，这将使年收入增加约 40,000 美元。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bleed
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/173863f5-743a-4d58-a219-b57a7e01cbf8.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>空巢老人的生活是另一个巨大的变化。他的儿子是大学二年级学生，女儿今年秋天开始上大学。谢姆韦尔已离婚并拥有共同监护权，他表示，他将深入参与孩子的生活作为首要任务。</p><p>他的航班时刻表使他能够灵活地参加孩子们的大部分网球和足球比赛。现在他们都在上学了，他想去看看他们比赛。</p><p>谢姆韦尔现在花更多的时间和他的朋友在一起，大多数工作日都会和他们一起吃午餐。</p><p>他不是一个活跃的交易者，但仍关注市场。他的投资组合<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/it-isnt-just-boomers-lots-of-older-americans-are-stock-obsessed-ca069e1a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">95%是股票</a>，大部分是指数基金，还有<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/AAPL" class="">苹果</a>等少数个股<span class="company-name-type">。</span> </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832732?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">保罗·谢姆韦尔最近再次开始打网球。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：《华尔街日报》的杰克·汤普森</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>他的父亲已经 90 多岁了，所以谢姆韦尔并不担心他大量的股票配置。</p><p> “我的计划是继续量入为出或量入为出，保持投资并为我的孩子们留下一些东西，”他说。</p><p>谢姆韦尔在休斯顿的房屋抵押贷款还剩大约 30 万美元。他的再融资利率为 2.99%，因此他并不急于偿还债务。</p><p>他驾驶的是一辆 2016 款英菲尼迪，行驶里程约为 80,000 英里。这辆车以及他为女儿购买的二手奔驰都是付费的。他每月全额支付信用卡账单。</p><p> “我喜欢让事情变得简单，”他说。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/archibald/1JhIu4HsU3kUrK8q6t8nArRD6-qm34M9iySjy14qk7vc-chapter-2.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> Jay Myer 积累了足够的积蓄，可以在 2020 年提前退休，因为他在 401(k) 计划中缴纳了数十年的最高缴款。</p><p> 25 岁时，迈尔读了<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/vanguards-founder-a-force-of-nature-11547812685?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">先锋创始人约翰·博格尔 (John Bogle)</a>写的一本支持低成本指数基金的书。他也按照著名选股家彼得·林奇的建议购买了个股，“买你所知道的”。对于现年 61 岁的迈尔来说，这意味着科技股和与他进行软件交易的公司的股票，其中包括家得<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/HD" class="">宝 (Home Depot)</a> <span class="company-name-type">，</span>他在几十年前以每股 3 美元的分割调整价格购买了该公司。</p><p> “我当时还很年轻，才读到有关退休的文章，但这对我来说很有意义。如果你降低投资成本，你就会保留更多的利润，”迈尔说，他的退休账户投资于七只先锋指数基金。</p><p>他和 60 岁的妻子安妮塔 (Anita) 开着二手车，并严格遵守预算，以便 Myer 从 22 岁起就可以向他的 401(k) 账户缴纳最高年度限额。安妮塔 (Anita) 一直担任牙科保健员，直到 2000 年他们的第二个儿子出生。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bleed
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/d872ec8a-8e9f-4719-9763-3d49c3645f1b.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>迈尔说，他决定提前退休的部分原因是他的继父是一位小企业主，喜欢旅行和与孙辈共度时光。</p><p> “他向我展示了你可以放下工作场所并重新认识自己，”迈尔说。</p><p>起初，失去稳定的薪水是很可怕的。当 2020 年市场暴跌时，他仔细检查了这对夫妇的每一次购买，甚至餐巾纸，但很快意识到，考虑到他们的健康储蓄，这样做是没有必要的。</p><p>这对夫妇现在拥有 420 万美元，一半在退休账户，一半在应税账户。</p><p>这对夫妇利用最近出售亚特兰大房屋的收益，以 925,000 美元在卡里购买了一套房子，距离他们经常见到的大儿子的家人有 2 英里。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832750?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">迈尔斯夫妇喜欢烹饪、园艺和旅行，并计划改进他们的新家。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：《华尔街日报》的 Kate Medley</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>他们每年花费约 130,000 美元，其中包括 5,000 美元的财产税。他们每个月在食品上花费约 700 美元，在健康保险上花费 1,000 美元。 （由于他们目前用现金储备支出，这对夫妇的应税收入足够低，有资格获得保险补贴。）</p><p>为了最大化他每月的福利，迈尔表示他会等到 70 岁才领取社会保障。</p><p>这对夫妇曾考虑出售一些个股，以将更多资金投入债券，但由于利润所欠的资本利得税而打消了念头。他们决定把最大的赢家留给他们的两个儿子。</p><p>迈尔斯夫妇每年的旅行预算约为 20,000 美元，他们正计划今年去西班牙旅行，他们的小儿子今年就住在那里。</p><p>两人都喜欢烹饪和园艺。迈尔说他很享受自由自在的时间。</p><p> “现在我有了更多的时间，我学会了拥抱无聊，放慢脚步，有时接受读书或骑自行车就足够了，”他说。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/archibald/1JhIu4HsU3kUrK8q6t8nArRD6-qm34M9iySjy14qk7vc-chapter-3.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>对于胡亨利博士来说，工作是实现令人满意的退休生活的一部分。</p><p>这位加利福尼亚州欧文市的外科医生过去每周工作长达 80 个小时，但现在他在假期期间兼职工作。 “我真的很喜欢旅行，”72 岁的胡说。</p><p> Hwu 是一名来自台湾的移民，他说他和已故的妻子于 1979 年来到美国。在芝加哥学习了五年外科手术并于 1986 年在密歇根州完成结直肠外科奖学金后，Hwu 搬到了南加州，他和妻子在那里抚养了三个孩子。</p><p>在达到医疗实践规定的 65 岁强制退休年龄之前，Hwu 开始阅读有关退休的书籍（他说还有《华尔街日报》的文章）。他开始打高尔夫球和泡菜球，还买了一把吉他，重拾了自医学院以来他几乎没有时间从事的一项爱好。</p><p>但 2016 年退休后，他错过了工作并开始接受以前诊所的任务。</p><p>每天早上，他都会问自己这一天要做什么。 “我不喜欢那种感觉，”胡说，他的妻子在他退休后不久就去世了。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832859?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Henry Hwu 博士于 2016 年正式退休，但在不旅行时继续兼职工作。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：《华尔街日报》的 Ryan Young</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>胡每年旅行长达三个月，去台湾看望他 98 岁的母亲，或者游览苏格兰、法国、德国、日本和瑞士，他曾在那里给朋友买了很多巧克力，结果行李箱都坏了。</p><p> Hwu经常带着他的吉他。最近在伦敦时，他给了一位街头音乐家 20 英镑让他让位，以便他可以演奏 Everly Brothers 的《Let It Be Me》。 “我不知道人们是否喜欢它，但有一位观众站在我面前，”胡说。</p><p>胡仍然喜欢参加医学会议和阅读医学期刊。</p><p>在 2017 年的一次会议上，他遇到了洛斯阿拉莫斯一家乡村医院唯一的外科医生 NM Hwu，现在大多数月份都会前往洛斯阿拉莫斯为外科医生接班几天。在那里，他喜欢徒步旅行并拜访在阿尔伯克基担任会计师的儿子。</p><p>在家时，Hwu 会去上吉他课，并经常见到他的女儿和小孙女。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bleed
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/f3b9dd2c-d95e-4677-81b1-f14a149509ca.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>他的房子价值150万美元。他拥有第二套房子，价值 120 万美元，每月租金为 3,500 美元。他每套房子欠约 50 万美元，但并不急于偿还抵押贷款，因为利率低于 3%。</p><p> Hwu 将其退休账户中超过 100 万美元的资金几乎全部投资于股票基金和个股，包括苹果、<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/MSFT" class="company-name">微软</a>和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/NVDA" class="">英伟达</a><span class="company-name-type">。</span></p><p>他每月领取 2,700 美元的社会保障福利，从 65 岁开始领取。他每年领取约 13 万美元的养老金，去年从每日工作中赚取约 30 万美元。</p><p>旅行是他的大手笔，每年花费 10 万美元。其他开支约为每月 4,000 美元，这还不包括他的抵押贷款付款。</p><p>他每年还支付 6,800 美元的长期护理保险。</p><p> “我妈妈活到了 98 岁，我有一天会无法照顾自己，”他说。 “我想减轻孩子们的负担。” </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/archibald/1JhIu4HsU3kUrK8q6t8nArRD6-qm34M9iySjy14qk7vc-chapter-4.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>在成长过程中，鲍勃·弗雷（Bob Frey）从未想过自己会成为百万富翁退休。</p><p>从西点军校毕业后，他在现役期间获得了硕士学位，然后通过陆军预备役奖学金和退伍军人法案获得了兽医学位。他担任预备役军官 26 年，60 岁退休。他从 30 多岁开始就用尽了退休计划缴款。</p><p>日子有时很艰难，比如当他借了大约 15 万美元开办兽医诊所时。多年来，他卖掉了三项业务，其中包括两家兽医诊所。他说，这些退出极大地增加了他的价值。</p><p>如今，80 岁的鲍勃和 75 岁的妻子帕特·弗雷已经存下了约 610 万美元，其中几乎一半投资于个人退休账户。</p><p>弗雷每年领取 60,000 美元的军事养老金，加上每年约 14,000 美元的退伍军人伤残补偿金，因为他在越南服役后出现了听力损失。这对夫妇从社会保障金中总共领取了约 56,000 美元。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bleed
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/b82deef5-2fa7-4359-8b0c-802cb8012644.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> “我们拥有的钱比我们一生花的还要多，”他说。</p><p>这对夫妇结婚已有 30 多年，育有 5 个成年子女。 20 世纪 90 年代初，他们搬到了蒙大拿州博兹曼，寻求新的开始并更接近大自然。帕特继续她的护理生涯，鲍勃接受重新培训，成为一名认证财务规划师。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>您为退休制定了哪些财务计划？请通过下面的表格告诉我们您的经历。</em></p></div></div><p>弗雷家族尽管富有，但通常都会避免其装饰。鲍勃说他已经大约 20 年没有买过新的运动外套了。这对夫妇住在蒙大拿州，他们说他们不太用得着正装，宁愿穿着牛仔裤和运动鞋到处走动。帕特经常和朋友一起去大自然散步。</p><p>弗雷夫妇预计将花费约 150 万美元来帮助支付他们九个孙辈的教育费用。他们每年还向他们最喜欢的慈善机构（包括他们的教堂）捐赠大约 40,000 美元。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832798?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">鲍勃·弗雷 (Bob Frey) 在世界各地和离家不远的加拉廷河 (Gallatin River) 飞钓。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Rebecca Stumpf for The Wall Street Journal</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>这对夫妇没有债务，也没有过多调整他们的投资，其中大约 70% 投资于股票基金。鲍勃说，他们死后可能会向慈善机构留下约 100 万美元。</p><p>弗雷夫妇也很重视旅行，每年会拨出约 35,000 美元用于环游世界。他们曾五次访问新西兰，鲍勃经常将他对飞钓的热爱与阿拉斯加、墨西哥和南美洲的旅行结合起来。</p><p>他们还喜欢与朋友单独旅行。帕特经常与朋友一起前往欧洲和加拉帕戈斯群岛。她跳过了鲍勃的狩猎之旅。</p><p> “我不想睡在帐篷里，把麋鹿带出树林，”她说。</p><p>写信给 Veronica Dagher <a href="mailto:Veronica.Dagher@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">（Veronica.Dagher@wsj.com）</a>和 Anne Tergesen（ <a href="mailto:anne.tergesen@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">anne.tergesen@wsj.com）</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/2d22c5e9-a490-4c14-9b85-792395763a6e.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/newsroom-feedback/89ceea19-a743-45d2-8530-c974dc040b2e.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 11 Aug 2023 09:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/heres-what-a-5-million-retirement-looks-like-in-america-1abc76d9</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/heres-what-a-5-million-retirement-looks-like-in-america-1abc76d9<author><![CDATA[Veronica DagherAnne Tergesen]]></author><category> WSJ生活工作</category><category>gfx-contrib</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>老年健康</category><category>人口健康</category><category>健康</category><category>个人退休账户</category><category>个人财务</category><category>退休计划</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>老年健康</category><category>人口健康</category><category>健康</category><category>个人退休账户</category><category>个人财务</category><category>退休计划</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Amazon Wants to Deliver Your Order Without a Box]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>这家零售巨头正在减少数百万件货物的包装<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832983/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="亚马逊可以减少包装，部分原因是它已经建立了自己的配送网络，包括像纽约州梅尔维尔这样的配送中心，以减少包裹到达最终目的地所需的距离。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>亚马逊可以减少包装，部分原因是它已经建立了配送网络，包括像纽约梅尔维尔这样的配送中心，以缩短包裹运送到最终目的地的距离。约翰尼·米兰诺/彭博新闻<span>约翰尼·米兰诺/彭博新闻</span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001124909"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001124909"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/sebastian-herrera" itemprop="url" rel="author">塞巴斯蒂安·埃雷拉</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 11 日上午 5:30 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/amazon-deliver-prime-speed-packaging-a616a135"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>数以百万计的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/AMZN" class="company-name">亚马逊</a>订单在没有任何额外包装的情况下到达美国各地的家门口。门口制造商的盒子里可能有一台新电视。搅拌机看起来就像是从商店货架上取下来的。一盒婴儿湿巾或垃圾袋也是如此。</p><p>这一变化代表了这家科技巨头对其交付流程进行彻底改革的下一个前沿，首席执行官安迪·贾西(Andy Jassy)希望此举能够吸引那些因每周收到和丢弃的亚马逊品牌盒子数量而推迟的顾客。</p><p>该公司去年改造了其物流网络，实现了更快、更高效的交付。对于公司保持主导地位、降低成本和实现与气候影响相关的目标来说，消除或减少包装变得越来越重要。</p><p>亚马逊去年聘请帕特·林德纳（Pat Lindner）担任包装和创新第一副总裁，他说：“许多高级领导都认识到这一点变得越来越重要。” “我们公司迫切需要在包装创新方面迈出下一步。”</p><p>亚马逊表示，该公司交付的大约 11% 的商品现在到达时没有额外的包装，或者该公司所说的“用自己的集装箱运输”。顾客通常可以在结帐时选择是否需要额外包装或更喜欢没有包装的订单。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832954?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">亚马逊在其位于华盛顿州萨姆纳的测试设施中测试包裹是否能够在运送过程中毫发无伤。高级实验室技术员雷特·布鲁斯 (Rett Bruce) 解释说，该压缩测试仪模拟垂直压缩中的堆叠。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：《华尔街日报》的科鲁德开斋节</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>挑战范围从实际到情感。亚马逊需要帮助其供应商创造出足够坚固的包装，以便能够自行运输，同时又不会添加额外的材料来削弱其废除包装的整体目的。例如，它需要确定顾客是否不希望将一大包卫生纸放在家门口，让所有邻居看到。</p><p>亚马逊正在利用其对包装商品公司和其他供应商的强大影响力以及激励措施，促使他们改进包装以在运输中生存。例如，网站上的供应商可以获得消除额外包装层的激励。</p><p>虽然亚马逊因削减其标志性的棕色包装盒而失去了一些品牌影响力，但它认为取消额外的包装将为其客户带来好感，据称，其中许多人已要求该公司进行此类改变。</p><p> “有时你会得到一个巨大的盒子，里面装着一个非常小的物品，坦白地说，这些物品一开始就无法破碎。 And you wonder why they used all that material,” said Kenneth Levine, a 76-year-old in River Vale, NJ, who said he receives Amazon packages about once a week. He has yet to notice the option to reduce packaging at checkout, but said he would be open to it for reasonable and non-fragile items, like books. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=C72EA178-F0CA-46FE-B63D-3CE629CAF70C&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Famazon-deliver-prime-speed-packaging-a616a135&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> The pandemic has changed the way we shop. More people buying things online means more people returning things, too. WSJ&#39;s Dalvin Brown explains how some companies are leveraging gig workers to make those returns for you. Photo illustration: David Fang<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>There is also some chatter online that leaving deliveries visible could lead to other issues.</p><p> “The manufacturer&#39;s box doesn&#39;t have anything holding it shut, and isn&#39;t designed to have a shipping label slapped on it,” a user on X, formerly Twitter, <a href="https://twitter.com/orcakeiko/status/1523136883370254336" target="_blank" class="icon none">wrote</a> , attaching a picture of a computer part shipped without an Amazon box.</p><p> “Amazon didn&#39;t put my vacuum in an Amazon box — I&#39;m gonna be PISSED if someone steals my package by the time I get home,” another user <a href="https://twitter.com/THEHOLYKOREN/status/1687558410970017793" target="_blank" class="icon none">posted</a> .</p><p> Amazon Help&#39;s X account responded to both, citing its “Frustration-Free Packaging” that reduces the amount of packaging material. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/55ae24ee-8937-4c05-801e-4c3a26301b59.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> The company sees its packaging initiative as a critical evolution after the success of fast-shipping efforts, Lindner said in an interview. Amazon in the past year has doubled down on getting items to customers quickly by overhauling its delivery operations to reduce how far products travel across the US In its new regionalized model, many items stay near one of eight regions, The Wall Street Journal reported <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/amazon-overhauls-delivery-network-to-dispatch-packages-faster-more-cheaply-c10be8b9?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">earlier this year.</a></p><p> The massive growth in the company&#39;s warehouse network throughout the pandemic—it roughly doubled its US warehouse space in two years—helps, Lindner said. The less an item has to travel, the easier it is to move without extra packaging. Amazon has cut the distance items travel from fulfillment centers to customers 15%, and decreased “touches,” or how often a package is handled, 12%.</p><p> Amazon tests packages to be eligible to ship without a container, and it says that the system has improved through the use of artificial intelligence. The company performs up to 19 different tests at a facility near its Seattle headquarters that include compressing items, vibrations and drops from different angles.</p><p> One item the company put through its system was a package of screwdrivers. The screwdrivers were originally packaged using soft plastic that made it hazardous to ship without extra protection. Amazon helped the vendor, which it declined to name, design a new, six-sided container that would require no extra packaging.</p><p> Then the company used AI to identify other vendors with similar screwdrivers and shared the new container design with them. The company reduced the size of the package by more than half to about 125 cubic inches, making it less expensive to ship. For 100,000 of the screwdriver packages shipped across a 12-month span, the cost savings through an incentives program tied to the initiative would total about $34,000, Amazon said. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/atmospheric/amp.html?guid=C0596D80-1788-478F-AA8C-D31D0091F4BF" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> The Incline Impact Test System at Amazon&#39;s testing facility simulates inclined or horizontal impact during loading of items over 100 pounds. VIDEO: Kholood Eid for The Wall Street Journal<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>“There&#39;s a lot of stuff that we can do on the packaging design for things you never would have expected were even possible,” such as wine glasses, Lindner said. Amazon hasn&#39;t been able to yet figure out how to eliminate extra packaging for some fragile items such as vinyl records.</p><p> Brita, a seller of filtered water pitchers owned by Clorox, changed its packaging to be eligible for Amazon&#39;s program. The company began with its 6- and 10-cup pitchers.</p><p> Brita&#39;s designs for physical stores and e-commerce are different, said Kirstin Ganz, the company&#39;s brand director. To change its packaging for e-commerce, the challenge is to maintain the allure of unboxing without compromising the structure of the box. Brita&#39;s change included making its box open like a gift box to keep that unboxing experience a customer would have otherwise had with tearing open an Amazon box.</p><p> “Finding an e-commerce solution that delivers that sustainability, that safe shipping and that great unboxing experience is complex to achieve,” Ganz said. “It took us some time to get there.”</p><p> Amazon said it made its packaging changes in part because of feedback from customer surveys. The company in recent years has seen a decline in customer satisfaction on product quality and shopping experience, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/amazons-customer-satisfaction-slips-with-shoppers-11668986981?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">the Journal reported last year.</a></p><p class="articleTagLine"> —Lindsey Choo contributed to this article. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832946?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> If Amazon successfully delivers more items in just the manufacturer&#39;s packaging, there will be fewer loads with its signature brown boxes like this one that a delivery worker pulls in New York City.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: BRENDAN MCDERMID/REUTERS</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Write to Sebastian Herrera at <a href="mailto:sebastian.herrera@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">sebastian.herrera@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 11 Aug 2023 09:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/amazon-deliver-prime-speed-packaging-a616a135</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/amazon-deliver-prime-speed-packaging-a616a135<author><![CDATA[Sebastian Herrera]]></author><category>世杰交易所</category><category>摄影委托</category><category>WSJ公司</category><category>零售批发</category><category>伊泰林</category><category>电子商务</category><category>在线服务提供商</category><category>零售</category><category>技术</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>Products/Services</category><category> Product/Service Disruptions</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>亚马逊网站</category><category>亚马逊</category><category>亚马逊</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>products</category><category> services</category><category> product</category><category> service disruptions</category><category>零售</category><category>批发的</category><category>电子邮寄</category><category>电子商务</category><category>在线服务提供商</category><category>技术</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Women Own This Summer. The Economy Proves It.]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> By turning out in groups, women created a multiplier effect and propelled watershed success for the &#39;Barbie&#39; movie, Beyoncé and Taylor Swift. <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833253/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>照片插图由 Emil Lendof/《华尔街日报》提供； Warner Bros, Getty Images <span>Photo Illustration by Emil Lendof/The Wall Street Journal; Warner Bros, Getty Images</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001125137"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001125137"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/sarah-krouse" itemprop="url" rel="author">Sarah Krouse</a></span> and <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/anne-steele" itemprop="url" rel="author">Anne Steele</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 10 日晚上 9:00 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-summer-women-flexed-their-spending-power-dc2ce92c"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> A $1 billion-plus box office haul for “Barbie.” A run on bracelet beads ahead of Taylor Swift shows. Fringed cowboy hats for Beyoncé concerts.</p><p> Women splashed out big this summer, and tickets to major cultural events were only the start of the spending. Groups of friends, mothers and daughters traveled to <a href="https://www.wsj.com/story/beyonce-fans-are-sparkling-for-her-renaissance-tour-e1ada0d9?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Beyoncé shows</a> , bought Barbie-pink outfits, and did their nails in multicolor homage to Swift&#39;s musical eras. Then they went again with different friends and more family, amplifying the amount each group consumed and purchased.</p><p> Call it the women&#39;s multiplier effect—their spending is <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/taylor-swift-taylornomics-concert-eras-tour-local-economy-9fa1d492?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">a powerful force in the US economy</a> that propelled watershed commercial success for <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/barbenheimer-poised-to-deliver-blowout-weekend-at-the-box-office-9feef168?mod=hp_featst_pos3&amp;mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">the “Barbie” film</a> , Beyoncé&#39;s <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-beyonce-effect-swedens-inflation-feels-the-hit-417370a6?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">“Renaissance Tour,”</a> and <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/taylor-swift-eras-tour-money-511fdfcf?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Taylor Swift&#39;s “Eras Tour,”</a> which is likely to become the world&#39;s first to bring in $1 billion over more than 100 shows. Local economies have reaped the ancillary benefits, noted by the Federal Reserve in July&#39;s Beige Book, which touted Swift&#39;s tour for boosting the Philadelphia area&#39;s hotel industry. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=7DB7382C-957E-462E-9ECC-9126738B5FE3&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fthe-summer-women-flexed-their-spending-power-dc2ce92c&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Greta Gerwig&#39;s “Barbie” topped more than $1 billion in global ticket sales as of this weekend, according to research firm Comscore. It is now the first US film by a solo female director to cross the billion-dollar mark. Photo: Warner Bros. Pictures/Associated Press (Published Aug. 7)<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>“Women have always been a deeply underestimated economic force,” said Blair Kohan, a partner and agent at talent agency UTA, the agency that represents “Barbie” co-writer and director Greta Gerwig. They embrace shared experiences across generations, she said.</p><p> Not exactly activism, but more than just entertainment, this summer&#39;s hottest events drew crowds compelled by a common theme: art made by women that speaks to the experience of being female. The megastars on stage and screen seem otherworldly, but share stories that are familiar.</p><p> More than 80% of people who bought tickets to see Swift and Beyoncé purchased more than two tickets to the “Eras” and “Renaissance” tours, according to ticket reseller <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/SEAT" class="">Vivid Seats</a> <span class="company-name-type">.</span> Purchases of three or more adult tickets represented 27% of “Barbie” movie ticket orders, according to sales site Fandango, compared with 20% of all movie ticket orders through the service this year.</p><p> Jody Gerson, chairman and CEO of Swift&#39;s publisher Universal Music Publishing Group, said “Barbie,” Taylor Swift and Beyoncé tell stories of female empowerment in authentic ways at a time when many women feel powerless. “These are strong women who are not afraid to be in charge, and I think we&#39;re responding to that,” she said. “We subconsciously have rallied around them because their power gives us power.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833288?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Women have been dressing up in Barbie&#39;s signature pink and going in groups to see the &#39;Barbie&#39; movie co-written and directed by Greta Gerwig. Fans were excited on the film&#39;s opening day in New York in July.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Stephanie Keith/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Entertainment executives say they are learning lessons in branding and marketing from the phenomena, such as how a doll can be celebrated by adult women and men, too. Another takeaway: A brand or art needs to spark a cultural conversation to be a runaway hit. When a project catches on, it is essential to find ways to attract groups and encourage a sense of community for those that participate. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833591?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> Some men go to events in groups, too. They might wear matching jerseys with their favorite players&#39; names and numbers on them when going to a sports game. They go to movies together, but this summer, it was women who gathered the biggest groups of movie and concertgoers and opened their wallets repeatedly on those experiences to an unusual degree.</p><p> “The rallying people together, that&#39;s kind of the dream of these marketers, that you do their work for them and bring all your friends to the movie,” said Carolyn Sloane, an economics professor at the University of Chicago Harris School of Public Policy who teaches a course called “Rockonomics: The public policy of creative sectors.” She said that happens more among women than men.</p><p> Gerwig&#39;s “Barbie” explores society&#39;s expectations that women be perfect and, in the blonde doll&#39;s case, stay in their box. On Beyoncé&#39;s “Renaissance” album, she sings “Break My Soul”—“You won&#39;t break my soul, I&#39;m tellin&#39; everybody”—and “Church Girl”—“Let it go, girl, let it out, girl.”</p><p> Swift, who has <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-to-succeed-in-business-like-taylor-swift-8165be7c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">tussled with streaming services</a> for better royalties and reclaimed income from her albums by rerecording them under her own name, defied normal concert constructs with “Eras,” performing for 3½ hours at a time. When it rains, Swift plays on.</p><p> Ticket sales for women headliners in the top 25 tours are up over 400% from last year, said Lesley Olenik, global tour promoter at <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/LYV" class="">Live Nation</a> <span class="company-name-type">.</span> Sales of tickets for Beyoncé and Swift&#39;s tours represent 66% of all the sales for the top 10 artists on tour around the world, according to secondary market ticket seller StubHub. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833290?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Beyoncé performs onstage in June in Amsterdam during her &#39;Renaissance World Tour.&#39; The star&#39;s fans have been traveling to see her shows and buying up cowboy hats with sequins and sparkles, similar to ones the singer has worn, to wear as a show of appreciation for her music.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Kevin Mazur/WireImage for Parkwood</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> These groups of women are spending more on tickets to these artists and other female acts, too. Among the top 50 acts globally, the average ticket price for female artists is $660, compared with $245 for male artists, said StubHub.</p><p> Mary Ihedirionye, a 27-year-old program manager at an energy company, plans to see Beyoncé twice during her “Renaissance World Tour,” each time with friends and family members. The first show in her home city of Philadelphia with her cousin and a close friend set her back $1,200 for one VIP ticket plus about $300 for makeup and a new outfit—including a sparkly, silver, fringed Party City cowboy hat that looks like one Beyoncé has worn.</p><p> She bought a plane ticket to the second show in Atlanta later this month with a group of women, though the ticket cost far less there. She plans to spend a total of about $800 on the Atlanta trip. “They were the highlights of my summer,” she said. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834668?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> Some of the event spending came from pent-up demand for entertainment during the pandemic, when many households saved money while they were stuck at home. Much of it was also stoked by a culmination of economic and demographic shifts that have been under way for a decade or more, economists say, from women having children later in life, if at all, to female wage increases and shifting household gender roles.</p><p> Median weekly earnings for women in full-time and salaried roles have climbed 28% over the last five years to $1,001 in the second quarter of this year, according to the Bureau of Labor Statistics. <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/women-jobs-workforce-economy-international-womens-day-5fc372a3?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Workforce participation among women</a> ages 25 to 54 increased to 76.4% in 2022, from 74.5% a decade earlier, while the percentage of women with children under 18 who work also rose during that period.</p><p> “Instead of women making decisions about purchasing traditional goods that are in some sense a public good for the family, they&#39;re actually using their resources to purchase goods and experiences that bring them joy,” said Misty Heggeness, an economist and professor at the University of Kansas. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="945" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833316?width=1260&amp;height=945" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Taylor Swift has been performing for 3½ hours a night at sold-out stadiums on her &#39;Eras Tour,&#39; including this packed house at GEHA Field at Arrowhead Stadium in Kansas City, Mo.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Misty Heggeness</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> “They&#39;re controlling the household purse but a lot of that income is coming from the women themselves,” said Heggeness, who took her 15-year-old daughter to see Swift in Kansas City.</p><p> She was struck by <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/taylor-swift-fans-prepare-wardrobe-hydration-strategies-for-marathon-length-shows-2123930c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">the crowd&#39;s mood</a> : they were patient with each other in lines, where it could take more than an hour for the chance to buy a coveted T-shirt or sweatshirt.</p><p> Heggeness French-braided the hair of a woman she met in the line for drinks.</p><p> At shows, which are at once girlfriend raves, rallies and retreats, attendees trade friendship bracelets with strangers, a tradition among Swifties who have drained craft stores of their bead supplies in cities where the singer performs.</p><p> At craft retail chain Michaels Stores, demand among Swift fans for beads has exceeded the additional inventory the company forecast and ordered in anticipation of her shows, particularly in <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/tatpwyfmm-actually-means-something-if-youre-a-swiftie-d1972d77?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">alphabet beads that fans use to spell out lyrics</a> <strong>&nbsp;</strong> or other Swift sayings, a spokeswoman said. In cities the “Eras Tour” has visited, there has been a 300% sales lift in beads and jewelry in the days ahead of a concert, and a more than 500% increase in its jewelry category sales in Swift&#39;s home state of Pennsylvania.</p><p> “There&#39;s this continued movement toward sisterhood and celebrating each other and being kind and inclusive and being positive,” said Lisa McKnight, chief brand officer at Barbie maker <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/MAT" class="">Mattel</a> <span class="company-name-type">.</span> “What the &#39;Barbie&#39; brand stands for is in support of all of that,” she said.</p><p> Women are traveling ever-longer distances to be part of a community of fans, setting this summer&#39;s live events apart from past tours of the same artists. The average distance traveled for Taylor Swift&#39;s “Eras Tour” is more than 300 miles, more than double what it was for her 2018 “Reputation Tour,” according to Vivid Seats. Beyoncé fans traveled 46% further to see the “Renaissance World Tour” than they did for “The Formation World Tour” in 2016. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="925" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833289?width=1260&amp;height=925" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Fans at Taylor Swift&#39;s &#39;Eras Tour&#39; show at SoFi Stadium in Inglewood, Calif., this week have been going to her show in groups of friends and family, sometimes more than once, and wearing outfits that pay homage to her various albums.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Allen J. Schaben/Los Angeles Times/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> San Antonio mother Ashley Jackson&#39;s plans to attend one “Eras” show in Houston with her daughters ages 14 and 16, and a friend turned into two back-to-back shows on an April weekend. Four seats for Sunday night&#39;s show in the lower level cost $1,200 each and Jackson allotted her daughters $100 each to plan their outfits—each woman dressed as a different “era” from Swift&#39;s music. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="1694" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/58480ccc-7eb3-4301-9ddb-9d6e7a6f7e79-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> She drove about three hours from San Antonio to Houston on Saturday, paid for a hotel room and went with the group to get their nails done. As their excitement built, she couldn&#39;t wait for the next day and texted her friend “This is so fun, let&#39;s just go tonight.”</p><p> Jackson bought four more seats for $1,500 each an hour before the Saturday show. “I literally told the lady doing my nails &#39;no color, we need to go,&#39;” she said.</p><p> That money amounts to the cost of a car or family vacation, she said. “I recognize that it&#39;s crazy. But my daughters truly believe those were the best two nights of their life,” she said.</p><p> Jackson and the same friend are planning a trip to Portugal with their entire families next summer to see Swift perform there.</p><p> Many women feel powerless in the wake of the Supreme Court&#39;s overturning of Roe v. Wade last year. The crowds at these cultural events showcase women&#39;s agency and voice.</p><p> “It&#39;s a sense of solidarity that women are willing to pay good money for,” said Katherine Wintsch, CEO of The Mom Complex and author of “Slay Like a Mother.” “The tanks of women are empty. They are willing to pay a premium to fill them back up and that&#39;s what happens at these events,” she said.</p><p> Movie site Fandango said some 65% of “Barbie” ticket buyers have been women, compared with 50% of all ticket buyers so far this year.</p><p> Jeff Goldstein, president of domestic distribution, at <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/WBD" class="">Warner Bros. Discovery</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> said that while initially ticket sales skewed female, they have been roughly split 50-50 between male and female attendees since the film&#39;s July release. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="934" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833317?width=700&amp;height=934" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Taylor Swift devotees, known as Swifties, trade friendship bracelets with fellow concertgoers. Crafts retailer Michaels has been selling out of beads ahead of &#39;Eras Tour&#39; performances.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Misty Heggeness</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> The company and Mattel blanketed the globe with pink marketing materials, and in the trailer said explicitly that the film was both for people who loved and hated Barbie.</p><p> That messaging was part of <a href="https://www.wsj.com/podcasts/the-journal/mattel-bets-big-on-barbie/eb83d635-63c2-431d-96ce-087bf24c62f2?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">a marketing evolution for Mattel&#39;s brand</a> , as was letting the film poke fun at the company, including in a scene featuring a group of men in its board room.</p><p> “As a brand steward, why would I ever support putting the word hate with my brand? Why would I ever put that out in the world?” said Mattel&#39;s McKnight. “I had to get comfortable being uncomfortable. While that&#39;s never going to come easy, that&#39;s something we have to take with us as we work on future franchise and brand building efforts.”</p><p> Doing so meant the film broadened Mattel&#39;s audience to more adults and made Barbie popular among women and men of many ages.</p><p> Warner and Mattel intentionally released a limited number of images and snippets of content gradually to build excitement while not revealing the plot. They made plans to put life-size Barbie boxes in theaters that would allow fans to take group photos together. Shots of women in their Barbie boxes flooded social-media accounts.</p><p> In making the film, they included a wardrobe for Barbie that mimicked what the dolls had been wearing since the 1960s and included a lot of costume changes just as people playing with a doll would do, he said.</p><p> When Warner prescreened the film nationwide with theater owners, it insisted that they view it in full auditoriums, rather than with smaller groups because it wanted them to feel the group feeling, he said.</p><p> “Some of it is luck,” he said. “It&#39;s hard to capture magic.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="945" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833315?width=1260&amp;height=945" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Swifties decked out their cars and socialized in the parking lot ahead of the Kansas City, Mo. &#39;Eras Tour.&#39; Swift was last on the road in 2018 for her &#39;Reputation&#39; tour.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Misty Heggeness</p></figcaption></figure></div><p class="articleTagLine"> — <em>Ann</em> – <em>Marie Alcántara</em> contributed to this article.</p><p> Write to Sarah Krouse at <a href="mailto:sarah.krouse@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">sarah.krouse@wsj.com</a> and Anne Steele at <a href="mailto:anne.steele@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">anne.steele@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 11 Aug 2023 01:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-summer-women-flexed-their-spending-power-dc2ce92c</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-summer-women-flexed-their-spending-power-dc2ce92c<author><![CDATA[Sarah KrouseAnne Steele]]></author><category>世杰交易所</category><category>WSJ公司</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>名人</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>生活/生活方式</category><category>电影</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>名人</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>活的</category><category>生活方式</category><category>movies </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘Heart of Stone’ Review: Gal Gadot Shifts From Superhero to Superspy]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>这位《神奇女侠》明星在 Netflix 上与格伦·克洛斯和杰米·多南联合主演的惊悚片中饰演特工雷切尔·斯通，大放异彩。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-arti